                    chapter5: "Chapter 5"
                },
                chapters: {
                    chapter1: {
                        title: "Chapter 1: Introduction",
                        points: [
                            `<strong>Two Fundamental Computer Models:</strong>
                             <ul>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Turing Model:</span> Defines a computer as a programmable data processor. Core formula: <em>Output Data = Process(Program, Input Data)</em>.</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">von Neumann Model:</span> The basis for modern computers. The most crucial feature is the <span class="highlight">stored-program concept</span>, where the program is stored in memory along with the data.</li>
                             </ul>`,
                            `<strong>Computer Structure according to von Neumann:</strong>
                             Consists of 4 main components:
                             <ol>
                                <li><strong>Memory:</strong> Stores instructions and data.</li>
                                <li><strong>Arithmetic Logic Unit (ALU):</strong> Performs calculations.</li>
                                <li><strong>Control Unit:</strong> Directs all operations.</li>
                                <li><strong>Input/Output System:</strong> Communicates with the outside world.</li>
                             </ol>`,
                            `<strong>Three Main Components of a Computer:</strong>
                            <ul>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Hardware:</span> The physical parts (CPU, RAM, hard drive...).</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Data:</span> Information being processed, stored in binary form (bits 0 and 1).</li>
                                <li><span class="highlight">Software:</span> Programs (collections of instructions) that tell the hardware how to process data.</li>
                            </ul>`
                        ]
                    },
                    chapter2: {
                        title: "Chapter 2: Number Systems",
                        points: [
                            `<strong>Positional Number Systems:</strong>
                             The value of a digit depends on its <span class="highlight">position</span>. Each system has a <span class="highlight">base (radix)</span> and a set of symbols.`,
                            `<strong>Important Number Systems:</strong>
                             <ul>
                                <li><strong>Decimal (Base 10):</strong> The everyday number system {0-9}.</li>
                                <li><strong>Binary (Base 2):</strong> The language of computers, using only {0, 1}, called <span class="highlight">bits</span>.</li>
                                <li><strong>Hexadecimal (Base 16):</strong> Uses {0-9, A-F}. Used for a compact representation of binary data.</li>
                             </ul>`,
                            `<strong>Conversion Between Systems:</strong>
                             <ul>
                                <li><strong>Any Base → Decimal:</strong> Multiply each digit by the base raised to the power of its position, then sum them up.</li>
                                <li><strong>Decimal → Any Base:</strong> Use repeated division (for the integer part) or repeated multiplication (for the fractional part) by the new base.</li>
                                <li><strong>Shortcuts:</strong> Binary ↔ Octal (<span class="highlight">group by 3 bits</span>), Binary ↔ Hexadecimal (<span class="highlight">group by 4 bits</span>).</li>
                             </ul>`
                        ]
                    },
                    chapter3: {
                        title: "Chapter 3: Data Storage",
                        points: [
                            `<strong>Fundamental Principle:</strong> All data types (numbers, text, audio, images) are converted into <span class="highlight">bit patterns</span> for storage.`,
                            `<strong>Storing Numbers:</strong>
                             <ul>
                                <li><strong>Integers:</strong> The most common method for signed integers is <span class="highlight">Two's Complement</span>. The leftmost bit indicates the sign.</li>
                                <li><strong>Real Numbers:</strong> Use the <span class="highlight">Floating-Point</span> representation (IEEE 754 standard), which consists of a Sign, an Exponent, and a Mantissa.</li>
                             </ul>`,
                            `<strong>Storing Other Data:</strong>
                             <ul>
                                <li><strong>Text:</strong> Each character is encoded using <span class="highlight">ASCII</span> or <span class="highlight">Unicode</span>.</li>
                                <li><strong>Audio & Images:</strong> Analog data is digitized through 3 steps: <span class="highlight">Sampling</span>, <span class="highlight">Quantization</span>, and <span class="highlight">Encoding</span>.</li>
                             </ul>`
                        ]
                    },
                    chapter5: {
                        title: "Chapter 5: Computer Organization",
                        points: [
                            `<strong>Three Subsystems:</strong>
                             <ol>
                                <li><strong>CPU (Central Processing Unit):</strong> The "brain" comprising the ALU, Control Unit, and Registers.</li>
                                <li><strong>Main Memory:</strong> Stores the currently running program and data (RAM).</li>
                                <li><strong>I/O (Input/Output) Subsystem:</strong> Interacts with the outside world (keyboard, screen, disk).</li>
                             </ol>`,
                            `<strong>The Machine Cycle:</strong>
                             The CPU executes a program by repeatedly performing a 3-step cycle: <span class="highlight">Fetch</span> → <span class="highlight">Decode</span> → <span class="highlight">Execute</span>.`,
                            `<strong>Subsystem Interconnection:</strong> Components are connected via a system of <span class="highlight">Buses</span> (Data Bus, Address Bus, Control Bus).`,
                            `<strong>Advanced Architectures & Techniques:</strong>
                             <ul>
                                <li><strong>CISC vs. RISC:</strong> Two philosophies for instruction set design (Complex vs. Reduced).</li>
                                <li><strong>Pipelining:</strong> Overlapping the execution stages of multiple instructions to increase throughput.</li>
                                <li><strong>Parallel Processing:</strong> Using multiple processors to perform multiple tasks simultaneously.</li>
                             </ul>`
                        ]
                    }
                }
            }
        };

        document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
            const contentDiv = document.getElementById('content');
            const langToggleButton = document.getElementById('lang-toggle');
            const mainTitle = document.getElementById('main-title');
            const nav = document.getElementById('chapter-nav');
            const navLinks = nav.querySelectorAll('a');

            let currentLang = 'vi';
            let currentChapter = 'chapter1';

            function renderContent() {
                // Get data for the current language and chapter
                const langData = contentData[currentLang];
                const chapterData = langData.chapters[currentChapter];

                // Update UI text
                mainTitle.textContent = langData.mainTitle;
                langToggleButton.textContent = langData.langButtonText;
                
                navLinks.forEach(link => {
                    const chapterId = link.dataset.chapter;
                    link.textContent = langData.nav[chapterId];
                });

                // Animate content change
                contentDiv.style.animation = 'none';
                contentDiv.offsetHeight; // Trigger reflow
                contentDiv.style.animation = 'fadeIn 0.5s ease-in-out';
                
                // Build HTML for the chapter content
                let html = `<h2>${chapterData.title}</h2><ul>`;
                chapterData.points.forEach(point => {
                    html += `<li>${point}</li>`;
                });
                html += `</ul>`;
                contentDiv.innerHTML = html;
            }
            
            function updateActiveNav() {
                navLinks.forEach(link => {
                    link.classList.remove('active');
                    if (link.dataset.chapter === currentChapter) {
                        link.classList.add('active');
                    }
                });
            }

            // Event listener for language toggle button
            langToggleButton.addEventListener('click', () => {
                currentLang = (currentLang === 'vi') ? 'en' : 'vi';
                renderContent();
            });

            // Event listeners for navigation links
            navLinks.forEach(link => {
                link.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
                    e.preventDefault();
                    currentChapter = link.dataset.chapter;
                    renderContent();
                    updateActiveNav();
                });
            });

            // Initial render on page load
            renderContent();
            updateActiveNav();
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
